  "prompt": "Why are birth rates lower in developed countries?",
  "response": "There are several reasons for lower birth rates in developed countries:\n\n1. Economic factors\n- Higher cost of raising children\n- Women pursuing careers\n- Increased education expenses\n- Economic uncertainty\n\n2. Social changes\n- Greater female education and workforce participation\n- Delayed marriage\n- More emphasis on personal goals\n- Better access to family planning and contraception\n\n3. Cultural shifts\n- Changing attitudes toward family size\n- Less social pressure to have children\n- More individualistic societies\n- Higher costs of living independently\n\n4. Personal choices\n- Desire for personal freedom\n- Career prioritization\n- Lifestyle preferences\n- Environmental concerns\n\n5. Biological factors\n- Later childbearing age\n- Reduced fertility rates\n- Increased health challenges\n\n6. Policy influences\n- Limited family support policies\n- Expensive childcare\n- Challenging work-life balance\n\nThese interconnected factors contribute to declining birth rates in developed nations, reflecting complex social and economic transformations.",
